For other uses, seeÂ Human rights (disambiguation).

Human rightsÂ areÂ moralÂ principles orÂ normsÂ for certain standards ofÂ humanÂ behaviour and are regularly protected inÂ municipalÂ andÂ international law.[citation not found]Â They are commonly understood as inalienable,Â fundamentalÂ rightsÂ "to which a person is inherently entitled simply because she or he is a human being"Â and which are "inherent in all human beings",Â regardless of their age, ethnic origin, location, language, religion, ethnicity, or any other status.Â They are applicable everywhere and at every time in the sense of beingÂ universal,Â and they areÂ egalitarianÂ in the sense of being the same for everyone.Â They are regarded as requiring empathy and theÂ rule of lawÂ and imposing an obligation on persons to respect the human rights of others,Â and it is generally considered that they should not be taken away except as a result ofÂ due processÂ based on specific circumstances.

ï¿¼Magna CartaÂ or "Great Charter" was one of the world's first documents containing commitments by aÂ sovereignÂ to his people to respect certain legal rights.

The doctrine of human rights has been highly influential withinÂ international lawÂ and global and regional institutions.Â Actions byÂ statesÂ andÂ non-governmental organisationsÂ form a basis ofÂ public policyÂ worldwide. The idea of human rights suggests that "if the public discourse of peacetime global society can be said to have a common moral language, it is that of human rights".[citation not found]Â The strong claims made by the doctrine of human rights continue to provoke considerableÂ scepticismÂ and debates about the content, nature and justifications of human rights to this day. The precise meaning of the termÂ rightÂ is controversial and is the subject of continued philosophical debate;[citation not found]Â while there is consensus that human rights encompasses a wide variety of rightsÂ such as theÂ right to a fair trial, protection againstÂ enslavement, prohibition ofÂ genocide,Â free speechÂ or aÂ right to education, there is disagreement about which of these particular rights should be included within the general framework of human rights;Â some thinkers suggest that human rights should be a minimum requirement to avoid the worst-case abuses, while others see it as a higher standard.Â It has also been argued that human rights are "God-given", although this notion has been criticized.

Many of the basic ideas that animated theÂ human rights movementÂ developed in the aftermath of theÂ Second World WarÂ and the events ofÂ the Holocaust,Â culminating in the adoption of theÂ Universal Declaration of Human RightsÂ in Paris by theÂ United Nations General AssemblyÂ in 1948.Â Ancient peoples did not have the same modern-day conception of universal human rights.[citation not found]Â The true forerunner of human rights discourse was the concept ofÂ natural rightsÂ which appeared as part of the medievalÂ natural lawÂ tradition that became prominent during the EuropeanÂ EnlightenmentÂ with such philosophers asÂ John Locke,Â Francis HutchesonÂ andÂ Jean-Jacques BurlamaquiÂ and which featured prominently in the political discourse of theÂ American RevolutionÂ and theÂ French Revolution.Â From this foundation, the modern human rights arguments emerged over the latter half of the 20th century,[citation not found]Â possibly as a reaction to slavery, torture, genocide and war crimes,Â as a realisation of inherent human vulnerability and as being a precondition for the possibility of aÂ just society.Â Human rights advocacy has continued into the early 21st century, centred around achieving greater economic and political freedom.

History

Main article:Â History of human rights

