1800 to World War I

ï¿¼Declaration of the Rights of Man and of the CitizenÂ approved by the National Assembly of France, 26 August 1789

Philosophers such asÂ Thomas Paine,Â John Stuart Mill, andÂ HegelÂ expanded on the theme ofÂ universalityÂ during the 18th and 19th centuries. In 1831,Â William Lloyd GarrisonÂ wrote in a newspaper calledÂ The LiberatorÂ that he was trying to enlist his readers in "the great cause of human rights",Â so the termÂ human rightsÂ probably came into use sometime between Paine'sÂ The Rights of ManÂ and Garrison's publication. In 1849 a contemporary,Â Henry David Thoreau, wrote about human rights in his treatiseÂ On the Duty of Civil DisobedienceÂ which was later influential on human rights and civil rights thinkers. United StatesÂ Supreme Court Justice David Davis, in his 1867 opinion forÂ Ex Parte Milligan, wrote "By the protection of the law, human rights are secured; withdraw that protection and they are at the mercy of wicked rulers or the clamor of an excited people."

Many groups and movements have managed to achieve profound social changes over the course of the 20th century in the name of human rights. In Western Europe and North America,Â labour unionsÂ brought about laws granting workers the right to strike, establishing minimum work conditions and forbidding or regulatingÂ child labour. TheÂ women's rightsÂ movement succeeded in gaining for many women the right toÂ vote.Â National liberationÂ movements in many countries succeeded in driving out colonial powers. One of the most influential wasÂ Mahatma Gandhi's leadership of theÂ Indian independence movement. Movements by long-oppressed racial and religious minorities succeeded in many parts of the world, among them theÂ civil rights movement, and more recent diverseÂ identity politicsÂ movements, on behalf of women and minorities in the United States.[citation needed]

The foundation of theÂ International Committee of the Red Cross, the 1864Â Lieber CodeÂ and the first of theÂ Geneva ConventionsÂ in 1864 laid the foundations ofÂ International humanitarian law, to be further developed following the two World Wars.

Between World War I and World War II

TheÂ League of NationsÂ was established in 1919 at the negotiations over theÂ Treaty of VersaillesÂ following the end ofÂ World War I. The League's goals included disarmament, preventing war through collective security, settling disputes between countries through negotiation, diplomacy and improving global welfare. Enshrined in its Charter was a mandate to promote many of the rights which were later included in the Universal Declaration of Human Rights.

The League of Nations had mandates to support many of the former colonies of the Western European colonial powers during their transition from colony to independent state.

