The UN General Assembly

TheÂ United Nations (UN)Â is the only multilateral governmental agency with universally accepted internationalÂ jurisdictionÂ for universal human rights legislation.Â All UN organs have advisory roles to theÂ United Nations Security CouncilÂ and theÂ United Nations Human Rights Council, and there are numerous committees within the UN with responsibilities for safeguarding different human rights treaties. The most senior body of the UN with regard to human rights is the Office of the High Commissioner for Human Rights. The United Nations has an international mandate to:

...Â achieve international co-operation in solving international problems of an economic, social, cultural, or humanitarian character, and in promoting and encouraging respect for human rights and for fundamental freedoms for all without distinction as to race, sex, language, or religion.

â€”â€‰Article 1â€“3 of theÂ Charter of the United Nations

Human Rights Council

Main article:Â United Nations Human Rights Council

The UN Human Rights Council, created in 2005, has a mandate to investigate alleged human rights violations.Â 47 of the 193 UN member states sit on the council, elected by simple majority in a secret ballot of theÂ United Nations General Assembly. Members serve a maximum of six years and may have their membership suspended for gross human rights abuses. The council is based inÂ Geneva, and meets three times a year; with additional meetings to respond to urgent situations.

Independent experts (rapporteurs) are retained by the council to investigate alleged human rights abuses and to report to the council.

The Human Rights Council may request that the Security Council refer cases to theÂ International Criminal CourtÂ (ICC) even if the issue being referred is outside the normal jurisdiction of the ICC.

UN treaty bodies

Main article:Â Treaty body

In addition to the political bodies whose mandate flows from the UN charter, the UN has set up a number ofÂ treaty-basedÂ bodies, comprising committees of independent experts who monitor compliance with human rights standards and norms flowing from the core international human rights treaties. They are supported by and are created by the treaty that they monitor, With the exception of the CESCR, which was established under a resolution of the Economic and Social Council to carry out the monitoring functions originally assigned to that body under the Covenant, they are technically autonomous bodies, established by the treaties that they monitor and accountable to the state parties of those treaties â€“ rather than subsidiary to the United Nations, though in practice they are closely intertwined with the United Nations system and are supported by theÂ UN High Commissioner for Human RightsÂ (UNHCHR) and the UN Centre for Human Rights.[citation not found]

TheÂ Human Rights CommitteeÂ promotes participation with the standards of theÂ ICCPR. The members of the committee express opinions on member countries and make judgments on individual complaints against countries which have ratified an Optional Protocol to the treaty. The judgments, termed "views", are not legally binding. The member of the committee meets around three times a year to hold sessions

TheÂ Committee on Economic, Social and Cultural RightsÂ monitors theÂ ICESCRÂ and makes general comments on ratifying countries performance. It will have the power to receive complaints against the countries that opted into the Optional Protocol once it has come into force. It is important to note that unlike the other treaty bodies, the economic committee is not an autonomous body responsible to the treaty parties, but directly responsible to the Economic and Social Council and ultimately to the General Assembly. This means that the Economic Committee faces particular difficulties at its disposal only relatively "weak" means of implementation in comparison to other treaty bodies.[citation not found]Â Particular difficulties noted by commentators include: perceived vagueness of the principles of the treaty, relative lack of legal texts and decisions, ambivalence of many states in addressing economic, social and cultural rights, comparatively few non-governmental organisations focused on the area and problems with obtaining relevant and precise information.[citation not found]

TheÂ Committee on the Elimination of Racial DiscriminationÂ monitors theÂ CERDÂ and conducts regular reviews of countries' performance. It can make judgments on complaints against member states allowing it, but these are not legally binding. It issues warnings to attempt to prevent serious contraventions of the convention.

TheÂ Committee on the Elimination of Discrimination against WomenÂ monitors theÂ CEDAW. It receives states' reports on their performance and comments on them, and can make judgments on complaints against countries which have opted into the 1999 Optional Protocol.

TheÂ Committee Against TortureÂ monitors theÂ CATÂ and receives states' reports on their performance every four years and comments on them. Its subcommittee may visit and inspect countries which have opted into the Optional Protocol.

TheÂ Committee on the Rights of the ChildÂ monitors theÂ CRCÂ and makes comments on reports submitted by states every five years. It does not have the power to receive complaints.

TheÂ Committee on Migrant WorkersÂ was established in 2004 and monitors theÂ ICRMWÂ and makes comments on reports submitted by states every five years. It will have the power to receive complaints of specific violations only once ten member states allow it.

TheÂ Committee on the Rights of Persons with DisabilitiesÂ was established in 2008 to monitor theÂ Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities. It has the power to receive complaints against the countries which have opted into theÂ Optional Protocol to the Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities.

TheÂ Committee on Enforced DisappearancesÂ monitors theÂ ICPPED. All States parties are obliged to submit reports to the committee on how the rights are being implemented. The Committee examines each report and addresses its concerns and recommendations to the State party in the form of "concluding observations".

Each treaty body receives secretariat support from the Human Rights Council and Treaties Division of Office of the High Commissioner on Human Rights (OHCHR) in Geneva except CEDAW, which is supported by the Division for the Advancement of Women (DAW). CEDAW formerly held all its sessions at United Nations headquarters in New York but now frequently meets at the United Nations Office in Geneva; the other treaty bodies meet in Geneva. The Human Rights Committee usually holds its March session in New York City.

The human rights enshrined in the UDHR, the Geneva Conventions and the various enforced treaties of the United Nations are enforceable in law. In practice, many rights are very difficult to legally enforce due to the absence of consensus on the application of certain rights, the lack of relevant national legislation or of bodies empowered to take legal action to enforce them.

