There exist a number of internationally recognized organisations with worldwide mandate orÂ jurisdictionÂ over certain aspects of human rights:

TheÂ International Court of JusticeÂ (ICJ) is the United Nations' primary judiciary body.Â It has worldwideÂ jurisdiction. It is directed by theÂ Security Council. The ICJ settles disputes between nations. The ICJ does not have jurisdiction over individuals.

TheÂ International Criminal CourtÂ (ICC) is the body responsible for investigating and punishingÂ war crimes, andÂ crimes against humanityÂ when such occur within its jurisdiction, with a mandate to bring to justice perpetrators of such crimes that occurred after its creation in 2002. A number of UN members have not joined the court and the ICC does not have jurisdiction over their citizens, and others have signed but not yet ratified theÂ Rome Statute, which established the court.

The ICC and other international courts (seeÂ Regional human rights below) exist to take action where the national legal system of a state is unable to try the case itself. If national law is able to safeguard human rights and punish those who breach human rights legislation, it has primary jurisdiction by complementarity. Only when allÂ local remediesÂ have been exhausted does international law take effect.

