In over 110 countriesÂ national human rights institutionsÂ (NHRIs) have been set up to protect, promote or monitor human rights with jurisdiction in a given country.Â Although not all NHRIs are compliant with the Paris Principles,Â the number and effect of these institutions is increasing.Â TheÂ Paris PrinciplesÂ were defined at the first International Workshop on National Institutions for the Promotion and Protection of Human Rights in Paris on 7â€“9 October 1991, and adopted by United Nations Human Rights Commission Resolution 1992/54 of 1992 and the General Assembly Resolution 48/134 of 1993. The Paris Principles list a number of responsibilities for national institutions.

