TheÂ Council of Europe, founded in 1949, is the oldest organisation working for European integration. It is an international organisation with legal personality recognised under public international law and has observer status with the United Nations. The seat of the Council of Europe is inÂ StrasbourgÂ in France. The Council of Europe is responsible for both theÂ European Convention on Human RightsÂ and theÂ European Court of Human Rights.Â These institutions bind the council's members to a code of human rights which, though strict, are more lenient than those of the United Nations charter on human rights. The council also promotes theÂ European Charter for Regional or Minority LanguagesÂ and theÂ European Social Charter.Â Membership is open to all European states which seekÂ European integration, accept the principle of theÂ rule of lawÂ and are able and willing to guarantee democracy, fundamental human rights andÂ freedoms.

