The wordÂ natureÂ is borrowed from theÂ Old FrenchÂ natureÂ and is derived from theÂ LatinÂ wordÂ natura, or "essential qualities, innate disposition", and in ancient times, literally meant "birth".Â In ancient philosophy,Â naturaÂ is mostly used as the Latin translation of the Greek wordÂ physisÂ (Ï†ÏÏƒÎ¹Ï‚), which originally related to the intrinsic characteristics of plants, animals, and other features of the world to develop of their own accord.Â The concept of nature as a whole, the physicalÂ universe, is one of several expansions of the original notion;Â it began with certain core applications of the word Ï†ÏÏƒÎ¹Ï‚ byÂ pre-SocraticÂ philosophers (though this word had a dynamic dimension then, especially forÂ Heraclitus), and has steadily gained currency ever since.

During the advent of modernÂ scientific methodÂ in the last several centuries, nature became the passive reality, organized and moved by divine laws.Â With theÂ Industrial revolution, nature increasingly became seen as the part of reality deprived from intentional intervention: it was hence considered as sacred by some traditions (Rousseau, AmericanÂ transcendentalism) or a mere decorum forÂ divine providenceÂ or human history (Hegel,Â Marx). However, aÂ vitalistÂ vision of nature, closer to the presocratic one, got reborn at the same time, especially afterÂ Charles Darwin.

Within the various uses of the word today, "nature" often refers toÂ geologyÂ andÂ wildlife. Nature can refer to the general realm of living plants and animals, and in some cases to the processes associated with inanimate objectsâ€”the way that particular types of things exist and change of their own accord, such as the weather and geology of theÂ Earth. It is often taken to mean the "natural environment" orÂ wildernessâ€”wild animals, rocks, forest, and in general those things that have not been substantially altered by human intervention, or which persist despite human intervention. For example, manufactured objects and human interaction generally are not considered part of nature, unless qualified as, for example, "human nature" or "the whole of nature". This more traditional concept of natural things that can still be found today implies a distinction between the natural and the artificial, with the artificial being understood as that which has been brought into being by a humanÂ consciousnessÂ or a humanÂ mind. Depending on the particular context, the term "natural" might also be distinguished from theÂ unnaturalÂ or theÂ supernatural.

Earth

Main articles:Â EarthÂ andÂ Earth science

ï¿¼The Blue Marble, which is a famous view of theÂ Earth, taken in 1972 by the crew ofÂ Apollo 17

Earth is the onlyÂ planetÂ known to supportÂ life, and its natural features are the subject of many fields of scientific research. Within theÂ Solar System, it is third closest to the Sun; it is the largestÂ terrestrial planetÂ and the fifth largest overall. Its most prominent climatic features are its two large polar regions, two relatively narrowÂ temperateÂ zones, and a wideÂ equatorialÂ tropical toÂ subtropicalÂ region.Â PrecipitationÂ varies widely with location, from several metres of water per year to less than a millimetre. 71 percent of the Earth's surface is covered by salt-water oceans. The remainder consists of continents and islands, with most of the inhabited land in theÂ Northern Hemisphere.

Earth has evolved through geological and biological processes that have left traces of the original conditions. TheÂ outer surfaceÂ is divided into several gradually migratingÂ tectonic plates. The interior remains active, with a thick layer of plasticÂ mantleÂ and an iron-filled core that generates aÂ magnetic field. This iron core is composed of a solid inner phase, and a fluid outer phase. Convective motion in the core generates electric currents through dynamo action, and these, in turn, generate the geomagnetic field.

TheÂ atmosphericÂ conditions have been significantly altered from the original conditions by the presence of life-forms,Â which create an ecological balance that stabilizes the surface conditions. Despite the wide regional variations in climate byÂ latitudeÂ and other geographic factors, the long-term average global climate is quite stable during interglacial periods,Â and variations of a degree or two of average global temperature have historically had major effects on the ecological balance, and on the actual geography of the Earth.

Geology

Main article:Â Geology

Geology is the science and study of the solid and liquid matter that constitutes the Earth. The field of geology encompasses the study of the composition,Â structure,Â physical properties, dynamics, andÂ historyÂ ofÂ Earth materials, and the processes by which they are formed, moved, and changed. The field is a majorÂ academic discipline, and is also important forÂ mineralÂ andÂ hydrocarbonÂ extraction, knowledge about and mitigation ofÂ natural hazards, someÂ Geotechnical engineeringÂ fields, and understandingÂ past climatesÂ and environments.

Geological evolution

ï¿¼Three types of geologicalÂ plate tectonicÂ boundaries

The geology of an area evolves through time as rock units are deposited and inserted and deformational processes change their shapes and locations.

Rock units are first emplaced either byÂ depositionÂ onto the surface or intrude into theÂ overlying rock. Deposition can occur whenÂ sedimentsÂ settle onto the surface of the Earth and laterÂ lithifyÂ intoÂ sedimentary rock, or when asÂ volcanic materialÂ such asÂ volcanic ashÂ orÂ lavaÂ flows, blanket the surface. IgneousÂ intrusionsÂ such asÂ batholiths,Â laccoliths,Â dikes, andÂ sills, push upwards into the overlying rock, and crystallize as they intrude.

After the initial sequence of rocks has been deposited, the rock units can beÂ deformedÂ and/orÂ metamorphosed. Deformation typically occurs as a result of horizontal shortening,Â horizontal extension, or side-to-side (strike-slip) motion. These structural regimes broadly relate toÂ convergent boundaries,Â divergent boundaries, andÂ transform boundaries, respectively, betweenÂ tectonic plates.

Historical perspective

Main articles:Â History of the EarthÂ andÂ Evolution

