Continents formed, then broke up and reformed as the surface of Earth reshaped over hundreds of millions of years, occasionally combining to make aÂ supercontinent. Roughly 750Â million years ago, the earliest known supercontinentÂ Rodinia, began to break apart. The continents later recombined to formÂ PannotiaÂ which broke apart about 540Â million years ago, then finallyÂ Pangaea, which broke apart about 180Â million years ago.

