Central to the ecosystem concept is the idea thatÂ living organismsÂ interact with every other element in their localÂ environment. Eugene Odum, a founder of ecology, stated: "Any unit that includes all of the organisms (ie: the "community") in a given area interacting with the physical environment so that a flow of energy leads to clearly defined trophic structure, biotic diversity, and material cycles (i.e.: exchange of materials between living and nonliving parts) within the system is an ecosystem."Â Within the ecosystem, species are connected and dependent upon one another in theÂ food chain, and exchange energy andÂ matterÂ between themselves as well as with their environment.Â The human ecosystem concept is based on the human/natureÂ dichotomyÂ and the idea that all species are ecologically dependent on each other, as well as with the abiotic constituents of theirÂ biotope.

