AlthoughÂ humansÂ comprise only a minuscule proportion of the total livingÂ biomassÂ on Earth, theÂ human effect on natureÂ is disproportionately large. Because of the extent of human influence, the boundaries between what humans regard as nature and "made environments" is not clear cut except at the extremes. Even at the extremes, the amount of natural environment that is free of discernible human influence is diminishing at an increasingly rapid pace. A 2020 study published inÂ NatureÂ found that anthropogenic mass (human-made materials) outweighs all living biomass on earth, withÂ plasticÂ alone exceeding the mass of all land and marine animals combined.Â And according to a 2021 study published inÂ Frontiers in Forests and Global Change, only about 3% of the planet's terrestrial surface is ecologically andÂ faunallyÂ intact, with a low human footprint and healthy populations of native animal species.

